s as artistic influence, the coping strategies of minorities, the hypocrisies of conservatism, and the effects of positive and negative discrimination. Traveling from Harlem in the 1910s to 1920s Paris, 1930s Berlin, 1950s New York and beyond, this sharply observed, warm-spirited book presents a surpassing portrait of twentieth-century gay culture and the men and women who both redefined themselves and changed history.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Mai 2022) 0aGay and lesbian studies. 0aGay culture. 0aGay menxHistory. 0aHomosexualityxHistory. 0aLesbiansxHistory. 0aSocial historyy20th century. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / LGBT Studies / Gay Studies.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertYale University Press Complete eBook-Package 2017z978311063898140uhttps://doi.org/10.12987/9780300234992?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780300234992423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780300234992/original  a978-3-11-063898-1  Yale University Press Complete eBook-Package 2017b2017  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles